Duel to the Last Blood: MP3 Players vs. Cellphones
We will advise how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It is clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
However, there are many reasons to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
First of all these musical products do not come out as LP and from a qualitative point of view for this there is not even an objective reason.
If, however, hard-rock, jazz or blues vinyl is crowded on your shelves, at least you dream of such a turntable.
It also works with portable music, i.e. compressed music or simply in MP3 format.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend 8,000 crowns for a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan perhaps hardly digests the market’s twenty crown headphones.
Two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It is the battery life that decides.
Some high-quality music players can do much more than just play music, but they don’t do it by mistake.
There is no other current device as universal as the mobile phone.
Besides the primary functions, phone and text, it can read music and videos, record both and has a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse and maybe it can even navigate.
And if we consider smartphones and handhelds you will also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle that no refrigerator can grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the mobile also brings disadvantages.
More functions you use on the mobile phone and first the indicator on the screen will require the charger.
Reading music consumes a lot of energy.
Few cell phones can read music for more than twelve hours, usually, and much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more effective.
As for cheap cell phones don’t count that they can last for more than a few hours.
If you still add, from time to time, a few calls, get another charger to work for safety, this also applies to the most expensive devices.
But you won’t have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least 9 hours at continuous functionality with a charge.
Another problem is when you download music to your phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have the universal USB port and not all of them can be connected to the computer without special software.
Of course the music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few memory readers are able to do it without an adapter for minicards that are not used in mobile phones.
Readers, with a few exceptions (iPods), do not need any special software.
Simply fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players create themselves a multimedia library sorted by the names of the performers, album name, genre or by the user's classification.
Some devices reproduce only the tree structure of the folders, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some know how to do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobile phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device, be especially interested in battery resistance, memory capacity, quality and type of audio outputs and clearly ease of use.
If you need music above all from the background and if you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram you just need any cell phone that plays MP3.
This is clearly happening on any mobile phone.
You don’t have to worry too much about which formats your phone or reader recognizes.
MP3 players support them all, the majority of the music that comes to you will be in this format.
In addition to this format that belongs to the most common, the total majority of devices support music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (format used by the company Apple and its iPods).
The best mobile phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Just visit, through the mobile internet, the corresponding pages of the operator (or another provider) and buy the song or album.
This same service could already be a valid argument to buy a mobile-reader.
Unfortunately the offer of the operators is poor and is usually limited to hits of the moment of the radio.
The prices are not very low.
But it is generally assumed that this very way of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their cell phones behind them.
Anyone who wants to listen to a little snoop in their pocket while the MP3 player is forgotten at home.
But it also depends on this, if you always carry behind the headphones or at least the wireless headset.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every mobile phone, but only a small part of MP3 players, has.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of mobile-readers will be, for many, the price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than 3,000 kroner.
For 3,000 and 4,000 crowns you will already buy a very dignified walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of an input for common headphones.
The best and most technically equipped mobile phones and also with the 3.5 mm socket for common headphones, cost up to 15,000 crowns.
Instead, the advantage of readers is, in addition to others, easy handling.
The simplest ones not necessarily cheaper (see our choice) we really do it anyone to handle them.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of handling once with the common stereo or maybe the turntable, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally bumping into the start-up of the mobile internet network and consequently a giant bill for data transmission.
What device to take
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (M2 type, microSD etc.).
Also with regard to the purchase of the respective card, you fall within the 2,000 crowns.
But be careful
The basic models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones can do it with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, take Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1 100 kroner.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, take specialized mobile phones - walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual keys for MP3 and the convenience of the service so it comes close to the same MP3 player.
In this area Sony Ericsson has come a long way, which mobile phones of the walkman line have the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
The MP3 players of the above brands provide you with the same service and price category up to 4,000 crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery resistance (commonly 15 hours, generally up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Possibly
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer practically all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, something is missing here – a virtual operator that forces traditional operators to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be missing for a long time.
Of the fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive in Europe we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
After all, <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> also confirmed this, pointing out that the price of SMS is higher for us than for the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regularisation of roaming charges, perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high in relation to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacking the competition that would really like to start the clash.
Perhaps it sounds absurd, even here we have three mobile networks and coverage highly above 100%.
Mobile telephony operators, on the other hand, like to complain about the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense he also often emphasizes the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, who in the past has sometimes expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network no longer probably has many possibilities. (Moreover, perhaps it would be difficult now to find other frequencies).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry into the market of virtual operators has led to a significant drop in prices, to which then the traditional operators should have reacted.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, similar rumors were echoing in Britain as we did.
However, it has been shown that the place for operators of this kind exists and that they can be really successful.
After all, for example, we don’t have to go very far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year this operator has managed to win over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta to which U:fon belongs in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, they need far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not carry back, that is, relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the offer of the narrowest services
So for example Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS that cost at least half compared to its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be quite a good move to bet on a target group as well.
This operator focuses, so to speak, specifically on men.
"Real men choose Mobilking operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company who produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept can be asserted here as in Poland.
The press spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition from the point of view of services it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no possibility, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is ever an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"There is talk of the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not have much expectations.
The ignition of Mobilking will take place rather in the other countries of our area," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, the press spokesman of the financial group Penta, said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz.
Thus he indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not very supportive of this thought.
Rather, they try to do everything so that you don’t create any potential competitors.
For some time she has not hidden her interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefonika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And the sooner it is done, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile network operators.
We have already managed to make progress in negotiations with some of them," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator we will have perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, around its creation there is an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At the moment we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed us," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of the Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nika O2 press section mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is also used by other operators.
T-Mobil press spokesman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "For now we have not noticed any vital and beneficial commercial project for both of us, on which it is possible to continue to build."
“On the T-Mobil network, a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this point we will have to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon.”
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on meeting its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
We consider this, from the point of view of the customers, the most productive.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Competent authorities - with accomplices
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances around the U:fon creation testify that when operators care about one thing they know how to row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure was on <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> during the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This testifies to the information of public access from the web pages of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for which not to accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> commented: “The competitive environment of the mobile market has been little enhanced with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Regarding the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place on him and especially on his high demands services.
The attitude of mobile operators is surprising, however, the complete lack of interest on the part of the Czech regulatory bodies.
It is not only the attitude of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> that unfortunately in the Czech Republic – unlike Great Britain and other developed countries – has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
This, however, has taken on its typical position with regard to the whole problem.
"The virtual operator's entry into the mobile phone market would be possible after the conclusion of the lease agreement for the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer from potential buyers has probably not been attractive enough for traditional operators," said Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS External Relations Section in the answer to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators is perhaps not surprising.
Instead of the office that has to defend the interest of consumers and, moreover, deal with the fact that no one takes advantage of its position in the market, it is more than a delicate business.
Especially when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: “Abroad where virtual operators commonly operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services.”
But obviously the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices are not in the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Truly shocking in the whole situation is the almost emotional harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence arises on its own.
Just as the identical price of gasoline for all petrol stations is the result of coincidence and competition.
"The section has not found any signs of anti-competitive behaviour regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No trader has a dominant position, so he has no corresponding greater responsibility for his behavior on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be lacking for the telecoms regulator," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many controversial points.
Of course, there is <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s analysis of the relevant markets, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
On such a market, of course, no Czech trader has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator the agreement of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator, logically, has a monopoly on its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not admit this argument, for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS it should be a little alarming that three mobile operators proceed in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time, complaints from interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS is kept out of the whole thing.
We have already seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>'s rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the update of the recently approved telecommunications law, despite the fact that, from this, many experts expected the situation to improve.
This fact the representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS must know more than well, but perhaps their interests lie elsewhere.
You can do it when no one is watching.
While without us noticing it remains the operation of such pseudo-virtual operators, of which there are even some in Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their price lists for mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
These are usually companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only pre-established people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company towards the operator is listed as a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a major customer you then receive special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar pre-sales.
"If the cases you are talking about, which we will be interested in, could be a violation of the contractual conditions, and could result in the conclusion of cooperation with this company," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> answered the question in question.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
In other words, they derive a profit from the activity of these companies and at the same time – unlike the real virtual operators – they are not harmed in any way by their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns of possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it as the regular customers of mobile operators.
But that should be a little strange at <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
In addition, there is another issue for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes in the face of such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if it does not want it will not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile phone market has led to a significant drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all the countries where operators were born, traditional operators were more or less trying to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were virtually identical - market too small, to the limit too saturated, problems with the quality of services etc.
But in developed countries, in these cases, the regulatory bodies have intervened in defense not of mobile operators but of their customers.
Both with formal measures and with non-formal pressure, then came the creation of the first virtual operator and others joined him.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing the whole case from one to the other like a boiling potato.
From our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes it more than comfortable.
But let's not throw in the towel.
If the background information is correct and the virtual operator will really appear soon, the Czech mobile market will start again.
If one of the operators had consented to the creation of a virtual mobile operator only <0xC3><0x9A>OHS could hardly remain impassive to the rejection (discrimination) of the other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
