"It was full of garbage, scraps of clothes and pieces of barrels, posters, leaves, ropes."
Some residents, including some bloggers writing about “gentrification” of the East Village, objected to the idea of selling Extra Place, arguing that the piece of public property, modest as it is, should remain public.
Others have praised Extra Place as a rarity – a fragment of almost nothing changed city that should be left alone.
Jeremiah Moss, who has a blog called Jeremiah's Vanishing New York (subtitled, "The Book of Lamentations: A Little Nostalgic Look at the Endangered City"), published part of a Discourse on the History of the City that appeared in The New Yorker in 1952.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote: "Extra Place is a narrow, dead-end alley, dark even by day and bounded by rusty iron warehouse doors and shuttered windows, with week-old newspapers fluttering along the slums."
With a few exceptions, the road looked almost the same as a recent evening.
A rat ran nimbly through the back of the street near a door leading into the CBGB, which is now the site of an aristocratic clothing store.
On the walls were graffiti, and an empty 22-ounce beer bottle lay next to a group of cool abandoned newspapers.
Few passersby have said they rarely thought of Extra Place but suggest it would need to be a little embellished.
Mr. Fields, for his part, said he also thinks some people underestimate the attraction of the road in its current state.
“The best years of my life,” he said, “were in black, dirty, disgusting places.”
The bilingual debate: immersion in English
In this episode of Educational Look, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the candidates' position on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a senior fellow in California studies and the senior director of educational studies at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book “Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose a School.”
Attracting Hispanic voters is a complicated business.
Barack Obama’s educational projects are a significant example.
Obama’s campaign notes that, “African-American and Latino students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” which is true.
To combat these shortcomings in achieving the goals, Obama’s education plan specifically supports, among other things, “transitional bilingual education” for English learners.
Yet the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes classroom teaching of languages other than English, does not take into account his interest in bridging learning gaps.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles County.
The school’s students are mostly Hispanic and low-income.
More than a third of students, many of whom have recently arrived, are studying English.
But, among fourth graders, an astonishing 100 percent of students took the top-level test in the 2008 math state exam.
An equally astonishing 93 percent of fourth graders took the expert-level test on art-of-language-English.
This incredible result was achieved using a different ingredient from the one Mr. Obama preferred.
Sixth Street emphasizes review and exercise, constant assessment of skills, and an "no excuses" attitude.
Also, and this is where Mr. Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school’s obstructive approach to English students is “full immersion.”
The use of English emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in the context of education.
Ms. Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me, “We had a fantastic success with a student just coming from Mexico and if you had entered the class 12 months later you would not have been able to pinpoint which one it was.”
"It works," he observed, "for us it works."
Would Obama model a school like Sixth Street Prep to replicate it in other Spanish-majority schools with English students?
The school’s achievements make the answer to that question very easy, but education policy in its own party (the National Education Association is a long-time proponent of bilingual education) and its own continued support for bilingual education prevents predicting Mr. Obama’s answer.
While he agrees that immigrants should study English, Obama recently made the topic trivial when he said that people should stop worrying about “English-only” legislation.
Instead, he said, “you have to make sure your children are able to speak Spanish.”
If Obama really wants to close these achievement gaps, he should carefully consider the educational models that work rather than scorn or trivialize them.
