Rested Gebrselassie breaks his world record
Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia showed again why many consider him the best marathoner ever, breaking his own world record at the Berlin Marathon on Sunday and becoming the first person to run a 26.2-mile run under the 2 hours and 4 minutes.
With a favorablely flat race win in 2:03:59, Gebrselassie shattered his previous score of 2:03:26 last year in Berlin for 27 seconds.
At 35, Gebrselassie sets the 26th world record for a career so stunning that it produced a world championship or a world record at any distance from the metric mile to the marathon.
Last month, Gebrselassie skipped the Beijing Olympic marathon, fearing - perhaps too alarmingly, in retrospect - that air pollution would worsen his asthma problems.
Instead, he decided to run to Berlin.
In almost perfect conditions - sunny and 48 degrees at start, 55 degrees at finish - Gebrselassie won Sunday with a scorching average of 4 minutes and 43 seconds per mile.
As soon as half-skiers like Gebrselassie and Paul Tergat of Kenya went the long distances, the marathon record has fallen more than two minutes in the past decades, since Ronaldo from Costa del Brazil won in Berlin in 2:06:05 in 1998.
After Sunday’s victory, Gebrselassie told reporters that two weeks ago he had calf cramps and missed a week of training.
Clearly, rest left it cool, not rusty.
“I’m so happy,” Gebrselassie told reporters.
"Everything was perfect.
I started again a week ago, and I had some doubts today, but in the end everything went well.”
He has been a bit criticized – especially in Kenya, Ethiopia’s East African rival – for over-orchestrating his races, generally avoiding many of the world’s best marathon stars, relying on the forecourt as if it were a half-bottom race, and putting world records above the sense of competition.
But these criticisms rarely diminish the magnitude of Gebrselassie’s competencies as a marathon runner.
With the pace cadenced by four Kenyans on Sunday, Gebrselassie reached the halfway point in 1:02:04.
Two Kenyan elite runners, James Kwambai and Charles Kamathi, competed in Gebrselassie after the forecourts vanished.
Just over three miles from the finish, Gebrselassie made a final spike to break away from Kwambai, who finished second in 2:05:36, improving his personal best time by nearly 5 minutes.
Kamathi finished third in 2:07:48.
In the women’s race, Irina Mikitenko, a native of Kazakhstan who is now a German national, completed a remarkable year by winning in 2:19:19, the seventh fastest time ever.
Paula Radcliffe of Great Britain holds the world record of 2:15:25.
Last spring, Mikitenko, 36, was a surprise winner of the London Marathon in 2:24:14.
She missed the Beijing Games with what is described as a bad accident, but was cured to win in Berlin, making her best personal time of almost five minutes in the third marathon she ran.
She ran a race doing her calculations well, letting a quartet of Ethiopian and Kenyan runners leave with a large detachment, picking them up after about 18 and a half miles.
Askale Tafa Magarsa of Ethiopia finished second in 2:21.31, while Helena Kiprop of Kenya finished third in 2:25:01.
In a city apart, pride and processes of a black life
Tucked away in the expansive theme park on the outskirts of Orlando, a few miles from the splendor, the noise, the enormous, lies the quiet city where pride and the complications of the African-American experience come into life.
Eatonville, the first all-black town incorporated into the country and the birthplace of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as he described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no prison."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect for Hurston, Harlem Renaissance’s most famous writer.
Yet in many ways, the city he described — and which makes tourists stop by understanding it in the Florida tour guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers’ Project — remains a place apart.
She is as independent, dignified, and private as she was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, that "knowing so little of us, he doesn't know what's missing."
Even now, in a year when a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, was called up for an opening speech on race, many here remain wary of the outsider’s gaze.
“We are very cautious about how our story is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, a lifelong resident and a member of the city’s oldest church.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It is both a historical black power grab model and a community of nearly 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example in the shadow of the oaks of rural culture of the blacks of the south - sometimes disdainful, sometimes rewarded - born from American slavery.
Not surprisingly, residents here are both proud and protective.
And the concern for Eatonville's image really began with Zora, whom everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through sincere, dialect-rich books such as Mules and Men (1935) and Their Eyes Were Watching God (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Rout 17, a road that runs through the often-forgotten center of Florida into a backdrop of black history and human drama.
Low in both life and literature, Hurston took readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then diverted to more private areas.
"Out the street to the left," he wrote, "is the modern public school, brown with white trim, with its well-maintained gardens and courtyards, which Howard Miller always looked after, thinking he could just read and write."
She also mentioned widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever suits the passing rooms."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Clearly this was not Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
“Zora said it like it was,” said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson’s girls whom Hurston immortalizes by citing men singing coarse songs about their beauty.
He adds, "Some people don't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who frequently returned from her family moving to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalls that when Hurston was in the city, he usually arrived unannounced in a triumphant Chevrolt, smoking and wearing pants in a city that even today boasts of decent clothing.
Many inhabitants were fascinated, Mr. Franklin says, while others were sighing.
"People were always very happy to see Zora," Mr. Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging in his chair on the patio at the back above Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no great commemorative ceremonies, and no great conference.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his legacy to everyone," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a 2003 biography of Hurston.
A change took place in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to place a five-lane highway across the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the two-lane main road.
Orlando’s expansion has already pushed Interstate 4 across the city’s western boundary.
The proposal came as Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, in addition to other things, had ended the relative idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the community's front door.
“During that time, a group of white boys came and threw oranges and things at people sitting on one side,” says Mr. Franklin.
“We actually had a girl who got killed by that one time.
They threw a watermelon out of a car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston made a request to the Supreme Court for forced integration, calling his decision in Brown against the school office "an insult rather than an honor to my race."
Residents now say that the desegregation of schools, despite being positive in some respects, dilutes Eatonville’s cohesion and jeopardizes the confidence of its youth.
“Black kids were used to being hugged — I remember this — hugging your teacher in the morning, hugging your teacher in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, the daughter of Ella Dinkins and the executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a nonprofit group.
This lasted, he added, until the teachers and students came from the same place.
"You didn't hug your white teacher because your white teacher -- I mean, there's a cultural division there," Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped and created space for many more Zora Neale Hurstons - black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudices, as she did, with cheerful self-confidence and lines such as: "How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I just can't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long journey to Hurston’s license plateless grave and began fighting for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, Robert E. Hemenway's acclaimed Hurston biography hit bookstore shelves, reintroducing it into the American canon.
The highway project came just as his most famous daughter had again caught the spotlight.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began designing a festival dedicated to Hurston in 1988 to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state backed away from its street project.
"The five lanes of the resurrected highway brought what would be called high speed, a real pride for the city," said Ms. Nathiri.
Mrs. Boyd puts it more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped change the city’s self-image.
Those from outside the city like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started coming to church here in 1993, began to appear in large numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was added to the public record in 1998.
A new single-storey bookstore (called Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a repaved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the feeling of a side street in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1980s.
(It's 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to search for the story of Eatonville, for its meaning, are often still treated with caution.
A permit requested in advance is required for most of the interviews, some things — such as the murals on Eatonville’s oldest church, painted by a white man, which show black men in the fields — are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a plump teacher with a soft spot for bright red, still fear that their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet as soon as the Hurston festival expanded, a high level of citizen pride also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing his entire race: beautiful, problems and everything, neither better, nor worse and proud, creative, hardworking, silly and confused like other races and ethnic groups in America.
It is sincere civic affection what can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or for the Police Department, which he said might need help.
And even those who are younger, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"A lot of people, if they just walked in here, will think, 'Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,'" Alondra Kenon said after Mass on a recent Sunday.
“But if you really stop and take a moment to look at history, it’s really a pretty city.”
Here in New York we all talk fluently about finance
On the surface, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newspaper stalls and the huge television screens of Times Square, they wouldn’t notice being in the eye of the cyclone.
They would never guess that glass offices, nestled above their heads, bankers and hedge fund managers who monopolize New York City are living every day the worst “bad day in the office” since the collapse of 1929.
The porters shake metal carts for tea through the sidewalks, carrying muffin trays for breakfast meetings.
Latin Americans drag their feet between condominiums carrying, like human mules, 50 and broken ironed shirts hanging from a cane on their shoulders.
Employees are still waiting in line for their morning bagel at the food carts on the sidewalks, and it is still impossible to take a yellow taxi between 16 and 19 on a working day.
It didn’t seem like there was a real crisis, until, with all the talk of ruin and sadness, I decided to open a new savings booklet on Thursday afternoon.
Even though I had planned it to coincide with the late afternoon break at my JP Morgan Chase branch, a queue of about twenty was already waiting in line.
Not in front of the cashier's desk, to collect money or make deposits, but in front of the customer service desk, where old customers order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to the Macy department store and new customers open accounts.
Many of those in front of me, I would later learn from Starr, my "trusted banker", were in line for the same reason.
Unlike me, however, they have already taken the savings from smaller banks in places where commuters do business, such as those in New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They have taken the money from so-called thrifts (a bit like a construction company), credit unions and types of city savings banks whose branches only operate within a state, and they say they treat customers like family.
In the past few years, 15 of these banks have gone bankrupt.
In recent days Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, was submitted to the controlled administration, and while New Yorkers were heading home for the weekend on a Friday afternoon, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in savings deposits, was looking for a buyer to save it.
The employees and clerks standing in front of me, fearful of another collapse, were moving their money to a bank perceived as a safe haven, the bank that is asking for more bail on Wall Street.
The common New Yorkers in recent weeks have become competent in finance.
A woman at my trusted Chinese supermarket, speaking on the phone, referred to Lehman Brothers, the bank gone bankrupt, and its emaciated general manager Dick Fuld in all familiarity, as if complaining about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed concierge, almost fifty years old from my condo, has changed the subject from our normal topic of conversation about Brad and Angelina or the delivery of my groceries.
She told me, after my visit to the bank, "Now I have all my savings in market funds!.
