Isabel Bayon rediscovers the Sevillan essence of the dancer Tortola Valencia
A Sevillan dancer pays homage to another dancer equally from Seville.
Carmen Valencia Tortola, Catalan father (Firenze Tortola Ferrer) and Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the Triana district, and at the age of three moved with her family to London.
She was a free dancer and a specialist in oriental dances.
She led a fascinating life and pioneered female emancipation, such as Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and vegetarian, and advocated the abolition of the corset that prevented women from moving freely.
The life of this woman, who marked a revolution in dance and aesthetics in Europe between the two wars, has always fascinated Isabel Bayon.
"I would have liked to work with Pepa Gamboa and she offered me this character. It seemed incredible."
The dancer says: "We do not pretend to tell her whole life, but to collect her spirit.
The titles of his dances suggested some basic elements of flamenco.
So, "the dance of the butterfly" suggested to me a guajira, or "the dance of the snake" some tangos.
Her dance was sensual and I was told that my way of dancing is also part of this aesthetic,” she explains.
The staging includes two exceptional contributions: that of Miguel Poveda, who will sing Isabel again in one of his shows, as face in "La puerta abierta"; and that of the teacher Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to work with what had been her student.
"Matilde plays Tortola as an adult, the character of maturity.
I’m happy because he has agreed to work in my work and I feel very honored about that.”
The set also includes the musical composition and guitarists such as Jesus Torres and Paco Arriaga, the singing of Miguel Ortega, the Pulga y Moi of Mor<0xC3><0xB3>n; the percussions of El P<0xC3><0xA1>jaro, as well as the viola of Rafa La Viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfran Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez "who played the role of eternal accompanist of these artists who have always been spay and all round.
In the work there is also in some form the life of this woman who takes place in distant places, especially for that time, such as India, the United States or Russia, and then all of Europe, since, usually, she resided in London.
“I wanted to remember her, because I think she is one of the women who has had a huge influence in a given historical period and now nobody remembers her and much less considers her work as something of value,” Bayon said.
The show will begin today, at 8.30 pm at the theater of Lope de Vega.
