Talking in Sleep
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who talk while staying asleep.
The first time it happens, at most you take a scare, but it doesn’t really matter much.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquium.
It manifests itself with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have been told that you had spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example associated with an episode of high fever) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once in the month ...), the day after the baby no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason for this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes linked to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, nighttime fears, nighttime bedwetting (peeing in bed), or sleepwalking, but this is not necessarily the case.
As already mentioned above, it can be associated with very high fever stages, stressful situations or overexcitement.
In any case, it is a phenomenon that is still understudied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks in a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (shouting, screaming, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to see if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety such as outflow to the situation.
We have said that it is a benign alteration therefore there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stressful situation).
What you can do, however, is to consider a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the baby too much before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is tiring to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once the sleep talks appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It is useless, because he is not aware of what is happening, and you would interrupt his sleep.
Although he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if it appears very distressed and the episodes have a certain frequency it is better to consult a doctor or check where such great anxiety in the child comes from.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not the most common situation), do not fall into the temptation to question him for information.
You will get nothing, because he is asleep and therefore not conscious to organize his thought.
In addition, you are able to hear what it says but not see what it is dreaming to say it, so you need to pay close attention to the interpretation of the information and the conclusions to which it might lead.
Never tell your child that you might ask him questions during the night to learn his secrets.
Not even for a joke.
Such a thing causes enormous anguish.
In short, do not worry, it is nothing serious, it is an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
