The meeting - The blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And most importantly, it has regained the public’s trust, seriously shaken by the infected blood scandal in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
In the face of such a tragedy and public outcry, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, directed by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to disseminate recommendations to prevent the recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was delaying a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of devising a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its business, only 38% of people said they still have confidence in the donation system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve blood safety and field research over the next few years, we have regained the public’s confidence,” he said before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec’s population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases of the human variant of the mad cow in Europe, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the one who has been president since 1998, the year of its foundation.
“And we absolutely didn’t know if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which, when there are doubts and serious illness could result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, measures of exclusion are taken.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was refused.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that without any doubt this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This episode showed us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NATs) that allow to directly recognize the presence of the virus in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have reduced the window period, from the moment the person has contracted the disease to when the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be shortened to less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to detect them has thus decreased considerably.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
“In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion is detected.
I believe that today you can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover your health, says the head of the Héma-Québec board of directors.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen will emerge in the system.
Not later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
You have to be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary continues before stressing that in addition to having safe resources, Héma-Québec must also provide enough.
“Needs are increasing as the population ages.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the number of donors, which on average makes up only 3% of Quebecers acceptable as donors.
However, all healthy people who have reached the age of 18 and meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who volunteer as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is widespread, they will be rejected for a period of one year.
“With this 3% we are able to maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
Cases of shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they grow older and can no longer make donations.
It is now difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so hectic that it is difficult to find an hour to donate blood," says desolate Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec distributes not only blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being deposited with Héma-Québec which manages the only public bank of umbilical cord blood in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, abounds blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the inclusion in the bank of our thousandth cord blood sample and we plan to take more than a thousand each year.
They should start proposing them for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection practice as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
