Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In the September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, senior vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, the latter states that the world’s largest gold company has filed a six million dollar defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small publishing house squatted with the intention of initiating a “transparent public debate”.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of a defamation lawsuit, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this substantial difference is completely obscured by Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to hers.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the writers and the publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend a substantial sum of money in order to organize their own defense and fight, with decidedly odd weapons, against an army of lawyers funded by the practically bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, in these unequal-arms struggles, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual settlement that muzzles the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to speak out again on the issue.
If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public debate, it is in front of the public that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is happening in many countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada the debates are usually held with an exchange of views and not with a beating.
It would therefore have been enough for the company to open its books, its documents, and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of teams of independent researchers that could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold doesn’t seem to have too much confidence in public opinion and badly rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of Canada Nero.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand a "public" debate when his contempt for that same audience is quite evident?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers exclusively to the lavishly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; here is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democratic system, even denigrators have the right to speak out.
What Barrack Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does so primarily because it rejects the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This audience is ready to listen to Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civil exchanges of opinion, and not from the perspective of what many perceive as a kind of gag (seeking the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Black Canada an ultimatum urging them to suspend the use of that word...)
Beyond Garver’s surreal discourse, the Barrack Gold lawsuit is a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in any democratic society.
It denies en bloc the right to citation of authentic sources and to debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss topics that are inconvenient to the richest companies in the world, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following scientific norms as the authors of Canada Nero do.
You have the right to reply.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we are a part, has been able to handle debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's excessive measures clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it does not seek a transparent debate at all.
This is to the detriment of the university world, as is the public debate in Canada itself, and it is time for governments to take measures to limit abusive complaints.
Operation – rescue for Wall Street – Dialogue between Republicans and Democrats
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, representatives of the Republican and Democratic side, finally reached an agreement on the largest bailout plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan, which aims to curb the financial crisis that has been plaguing Wall Street for months, has yet to be ratified by both houses of Congress.
It includes, in particular, checks on its effective implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms to guarantee the reimbursement of public money, new provisions to contain the number of houses forfeited, as well as a right of inspection on the salaries paid to the managers of the protected companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican Rep. Judd Gregg announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
“We have made great progress towards an effective market deal,” said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
“Every decision has been made in such a way as to safeguard the American economy and people from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street,” he said.
“It’s the crucial point: if we hadn’t acted in this way, inestimable disappointments and turmoil would have spilled over into the daily lives of Americans,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of a new bankruptcy on investors.
The time limit agreed corresponded to the opening of the markets this morning.
Later joining the negotiations, the two candidates for the US presidential elections showed themselves quite in favour of the agreement, without, however, avoiding expressing their dissatisfaction with the adoption of extreme solutions.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama is credited with having added some provisions to the agreement, particularly the one that will allow owners to keep their domicile and the one inherent in the salaries intended for executives of companies covered by the state.
“When you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there’s nothing to rejoice about.
But these measures are necessary," he said on U.S. television.
Interviewed on another channel to know if he will vote in favor of the plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to analyze the details, but I hope so."
“From what I’ve read, it’s something that we all have to digest and that will allow us to move forward.”
The option of non-intervention is simply unacceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to repurchase with taxpayer money the doubtful, risky and unsold assets of American financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis due to the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of mortgage-at-risk (mortgage) loans, then extended to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and resulted in the freezing of liquidity and the dumping of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republicans in office who blew up the first draft of a deal last week.
It seems to have come out of that dead end since the Democrats accepted that the “toxic” asset of some companies in difficulty is only protected by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to meet everyone in Congress, a provision was added that, if the government were to face losses over the next five years due to such a program, it could impose new taxes in order to maintain its own balance.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first sum of 250 billion to which a further 100 billion may be added if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of $350 billion should be ratified by a further vote of Congress.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get stakes in protected companies that will earn dividends in case of profit and which it can resell when the waters have calmed down.
According to the plan, the federal government will have the opportunity to delay foreclosure procedures related to real estate loans and to set limits on the remuneration and severance payments paid to the managers of the companies involved.
As of today, the plan’s architects would like to submit it to the House of Representatives vote, and to the Senate vote on Wednesday.
