In fact, yesterday there were several votes against the project, both in the Republican and Democratic side.
“Obviously, Washington doesn’t hear you,” Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House finance committee, told voters.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
Not to take advantage of taxpayers.
Leader of a small group in Congress dubbed “the caucus of skeptics,” Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman presents the situation differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel Laureates, have written to us to say: We ask Congress not to draw hasty conclusions and to carefully examine the way forward,” he said.
At the same time, Europe was once again witnessing the test of the global nature of the crisis.
