The Psychology of Excess Bidding: Why Spend More Money?
At auctions, buyers are likely to spend more, overvalue the goods.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have managed to uncover the neuro-economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study appeared in the journal Science men do not want to be left behind in a race such as the eBay auction, so they are willing to pay a higher price as well.
The research sought to trace the nervous pattern of this "match" at the level of the nervous system through experimental rods.
One group of volunteers played the lotto, the other group of players participated in an auction while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method they examined the active brain areas of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games participants could win money, but in the auction game, in which the substantial element is to bid more than the other, the striatum under the cerebral cortex comes into intensive operation when you lose to the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price increase is explained by avoiding the vehement reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group conducted a financial tracking survey.
In this survey three groups bid against a partner under different conditions.
They told the control group what the real value of the product in question was and they made their bet.
To another group besides this they promised that in case of winning they will receive another prize of 15 dollars.
The third group would have received $15 before the auction, but the group members would have lost the money in the event of a loss at the auction.
The difference between the two groups consisted in the fact that for one of them the win was emphasized, while for the other the loss.
By testing the neurologists’ hypothesis, the members of the group that played “against loss” were willing to make higher stakes than the control or “winning” group.
“These results are not deducible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
These in fact so far explained the phenomena found at auctions with the joy of winning and with the avoidance of risk.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image helped to resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so we came to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University’s Faculty of Economics.
Hepatitis: When to see a doctor?
Nearly half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver diseases are among the leading causes of death.
In Hungary, the number of hepatitis patients is one hundred thousand, of which only 7,000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name for contagious liver diseases caused by several viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. infected food and water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal discharge, saliva).
For those who travel, it is useful to get vaccinated against the A and B virus, against C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellowish spots form on the skin and the whites of the eyes, the stools become light and the urine dark, healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die each year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not know they have contracted the disease because pathogens subtly destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and perform regular medical tests.
This disease is much more common than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattooed.
In the world today, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease, it is worth contacting the family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so the infectious power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
September 30th is World Hepatitis Day, first organized worldwide in 2004 by disease associations.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith functions as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at the University of Oxford ran an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God affects the feeling of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
As part of the rather bizarre investigation, an electroshock was carried out on 12 Catholic believers and atheists, while all were observing a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploratory technique of the human brain, it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first of a series of research in which scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University take part in addition to academics.
The test was carried out exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked the participants to focus on two paintings, the virgin Mary painted in the seventeenth century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with Leonardo da Vinci's hermeline painted in the fifteenth century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary would give rise to a sort of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's painting was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and they considered it to have a calming effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time frame received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe", as if "someone took care" of them and "they were calm and were pervaded by peace".
Looking at the religious-themed image they found 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that such a result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but you have to find the right image.
“We have to look for an image that they have very positive feelings toward, like a mother or a father,” he said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it manages to change our personality,” Wright said.
After the excellent results, only the question remains whether the painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of such a caliber is presented to believers, what effect could it have on the control of pain?
Would the vision of a quality virgin Mary bring better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On the 10th birthday, Google can claim to be as much in people’s pockets as in the sky above their heads; it knows where they’ve spent their holidays, which clinic they attend, and what interests them.
However, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company’s directors, this is not enough.
What concerns the skeptics who make a comparison with the Orwellian nightmare, they do not see the substance of the web 2.0.
Recently Eric Schmidt told the Financial Times that Google’s main purpose is to collect as much personal data of its users as possible and this is necessary to stick to the original goal of the founders of Google which was: “let’s put all the information in the world into a system!”
According to the director of Google interviewed the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, it is still at the beginning of being able to manage all the information.
When asked what will happen in five years’ time, Schmidt replied: “Would you like to know how to answer questions like ‘what do I do tomorrow?’ or ‘what would be the right job for me?’, but the software doesn’t know how to answer seemingly simple questions because it doesn’t know enough about users.”
Not all Internet users are aware that during their Internet searches, exactly the words they are looking for are recorded, from which IP address they are searched and on which page the interested parties stop after the search.
By means of the Personalized Search started two years ago, users can memorize their browsing history, they can relate to what they have searched and clicked on, then in the long run they will generate much better tailored results; on this same logic is based Recommendations with which the system offers us products and services according to our previously stated and recorded preferences.
What if my data is being used against me, if they look at what I do? - ask users concerned about Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, Internet users’ counter-reactions are provoked by the fear felt for the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not for the sense of guilt, for the fear of punishment, for the desire for freedom or even for the rebellion to power.
However, one fact is confirmed, namely that all the expressions sought are not only recorded but in justified cases can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing defends the personal rights of Internet users.
Perhaps the most striking example of this in recent times has been the coordinated action against pedophiles in Brazil, in which Google forwarded to the Brazilian government the information that made it possible to identify pedophiles from the Orkut community page maintained by Google.
Internet users worried about personal rights instead sighed for relief in May when the company - in agreement with the electronic legal protection association EFF - successfully proved the truth in court against the FBI: even after that you can not force Google with any point of the constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time the federal government has successfully ripped out nearly 50,000 web addresses and a thousand search expressions obtained in reference to the confirmation of the child protection law passed years earlier, but still failed to get individual user search lists and the entire list of web pages and keywords dating back to two months.)
Google’s judgment is therefore quite contradictory: those who fear to provide their personal data scourge Google because they believe that this will affect their intimate sphere and privacy by starting to use its services and rise with the rebellion due to the multinationals that stand out for the conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and the proliferation of enthusiasts, activists and computer users who have appeared in numerous countries see in them the future generation of big companies, the "cool corporation", unlike their rival, Microsoft liquidated as conqueror of the world because of Windows, although both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its services, the source code is kept always up to date and the program package is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official practice of the software giant.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which implies one of the keywords most often repeated in recent years, the web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is all about collaboration, intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal and while the size of these changes for each individual, the substance is the same: to show ourselves.
An average young person can create profiles on multiple community pages, from Facebook to Xanga, can link them with other services such as Twitter or last.fm that list their musical tastes, all of these can be inserted into systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also write blogs on which their latest photo galleries automatically appear stored on Flickr or Picasa.
Meanwhile we read of numerous exemplary cases from which it is clear that the girl, seeing the series of photos taken in the morning by the common tour of friends, comes easily to know with whom she spent the night her perfidious boyfriend or a company can fire his employee because he wrote a sincere opinion on the corporate summit: one thing is sure, the concept of privacy has now completely reconsidered.
Those who live a life online make sure to show themselves and so we can formulate the fundamental thesis that hides behind the behavior of young people.
Those who want to hide something or just want to avoid the monopoly of Google can do it (starting for example with Scroogle using the Google search system but at the same time does not voluntarily leave traces).
There are not a few people who do not purposely register to community pages to not be found, the online applications of Google, from word processing to image management and news collection, can be replaced with alternative versions not related to huge server parks and that do not make up our best profile so far.
The public is not even waiting in secret for the moment when Google will pull out its claws.
Currently the company with its $156 billion in value is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords / AdSense advertising spaces threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, services introduced in record time instead cause major hardships not only to Microsoft but also to numerous software development companies.
However, the critical observers next to all this find alarming points: the company summit, for example, completely rejected the protest of the employees after having doubled the right of the company kindergarten, considered too expensive the repeated daily catering interests of the employees, all this however diminishes in the face of the fact that in 2006 Google has bowed the head to the Chinese government and under their agreement all the results will be filtered.
An internal rule of the company seems to be not to advertise a new service in advance but only when it will be usable, one thing is however certain, that the foreseeable problems of the next months and years will move the world at a point: while some believe that the project of scanning and archiving books and magazines of Google will take on such proportions that the company will soon find itself in front of this American Supreme Court Health, others we can refer to
The fact that Google is building a genetic database can offer good material to the next generation of science fiction writers, the Scroogled tale of the famous Cory Doctorow describes the future with Orwellian accents, in which a man with Google data can be approached in an alarming way.
