Intelligent machine mimics the flight of the hornet
What could be the best method to develop anti-collision technologies other than mimicking the sensors of obstacles found in nature?
For example, bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the hornets gave Nissan engineers the initial strategic inspiration on how to build the next generation of collision-proofing systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimicry robot BR23C, a robotic minicar with the properties of bees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system capable of avoiding all collisions.
Flying bees form their own oval personal space that really looks a lot like our protective shield - explained Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technologies and research and development at the exhibition.
Important is the role of the bee's view, capable of a 300-degree view in each direction.
The engineers drew on the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the bee's view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately turns it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels of the necessary size to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, in a different way from the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If this were not the case, the robot car would not be able to react quickly to avoid collisions,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaging and innermost layer of the protective shield, within which collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees the deviation can not go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to avoid other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lighter, high energy density lithium polymer batteries, which means their lifespan is longer than those of lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the instantaneousness of the intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of the data or even less the ability to store it.
This robot has to process some inputs in a matter of seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous manoeuvre data, so it only uses a memory of a few tens of KB.
There is no need for gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, they predict at Nissan, within 10 years can be installed on standard vehicles.
Further possibilities of application can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system that avoiding the obstacles present on the road leads to the destination.
