Work accidents, Napolitano: "Critical prevention"
Every day in Italy, 2,500 accidents occur at work, 3 people die and 27 remain permanently disabled.
For 2007, Inail data confirm that white deaths were around 1,200.
Figures that testify to the seriousness of a phenomenon that remains one of the main causes of death and causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
To draw the attention of institutions, social forces and the media to this dramatic issue, today Anmil celebrates in all the provinces of Italy the 58th National Day for Victims of Accidents at Work, institutionalized on the second Sunday of October.
"The worrying data released by Anmil and the same tragic chronicles of these days confirm how crucial the issue of prevention at work is," says the president of the Republic Giorgio Napolitano, in the message sent to the president of Anmil, National Association for the Mutilated and Invalid of Work, Pietro Mercandelli.
The head of state expresses his "strong appreciation for the constant associative commitment in favor of prevention in the workplace, the protection of injured workers, the assistance of the families of the victims and the awareness of public opinion".
“There has been, of course, an indignant ‘enough’, sincerely shared, in the face of tragedies that, because of their size, arouse the clamor of the media and the involvement of public opinion but the daily reality proposes us again dramatic cases, even repetitive in their dynamics.
Napolitano does not hide that "there is undoubtedly also a problem of resources: it is decisive to invest in training and information.
Particular significance is given to the numerous initiatives promoted in the field of education for a more direct awareness on the part of young people entering the world of work.
It is necessary to keep the attention to the phenomenon alive, not to linger in the alarm about its social gravity, to apply and improve the legislative norms.
For his part, the President of the Chamber Gianfranco Fini stressed "that the phenomenon of white deaths constitutes an absolute social emergency, which offends the conscience of each of us and imposes on all institutions a determined commitment to put an urgent end to it".
"The data on occupational injuries seem to indicate a slight positive trend, but that does not take away from the fact that the number of white deaths is still impressive," said the president of Anmil Pietro Mercandelli.
“We would not want this ‘downward trend’ to result in less attention, because it is precisely when attention is relaxed that tragedy explodes.
