"The objective is therefore to give back to the worker the insurance guarantee - he added - so that the fate of those who are injured does not have to depend on spontaneities or grants from time to time ordered by the legislator".
Mp3 players on trial put hearing at risk
Listening to loud music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is according to the European Commission, which in a statement released in Brussels quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee on Emerging and Recently Identified Health Risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
“From this scientific opinion, it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable music devices weekly for more than an hour a day while holding the device at high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing ability.”
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at high noise levels may unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably,” says Kuneva.
“From the scientific findings, a clear risk emerges and we need to react quickly.
Most importantly, we need to raise awareness among consumers and make this information public.
We must also review the existing control systems, in the light of this scientific opinion, to ensure that they are fully effective and keep pace with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the widespread use of portable music equipment and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise from it.
Scientists confirm that there is cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with Member States and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music devices and related equipment.
Currently, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music equipment to 100 dB, but concerns are growing about hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
You can greatly limit these damages by resorting to solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee points out that users of portable music equipment who listen to music at high volumes (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week exceed the current limits on the maximum noise allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing ability after a period of 5 years.
This would affect 5-10% of users of such devices and their number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
