Elites in Danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the House vote against the $700 billion bailout launched by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were, and are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
The New York Times yesterday confirmed that the current crisis is splitting the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, instead, conservative, hostile to "those in Washington" and the world of finance, strong especially in the central and southern states.
The soul, for that matter, which has become powerfully alive with the vow of which I said at the beginning.
This is, however, only one example of the changes, of the great changes, which the current economic earthquake may foretell or already reveal: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not even here alone.
In both the US and Europe, the crisis seems to act as an accelerator for long-incubating phenomena that solidify in the new climate and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category State-sovereignty in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions that have, yes, deep ties with abroad, but that, first of all, see the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state, involved to a very large extent.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: namely how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and those families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems to be out of the question or not to have much to say: the obvious proof is given by the European Union which as usual divides between the different interests and between the different state strategies fails to decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of each individual state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and relaunch plans, new rules, and above all, the disbursement of funds: since when you get to the straits it is only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things in order.
And they also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, under certain circumstances, of which no market and no international organization will likely ever be able to dispose to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance that more recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the net, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will have to reckon with the very immaterial things that are water, the harvests, the oil.
All things that, look a little, can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth but are still absolutely linked to a limited space, to a territory.
So he who finds himself to be sovereign, certainly possesses several more cards than he who is not, to those who have the misfortune of living in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty, however, which foreshadows a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective needs authoritative leadership, the request of someone who knows how to take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for the existing leaderships, economic species, revealed to be so inadequate and full of shadows.
And together something even deeper and in a sense disturbing: a discredit, an insufficiency, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in an increasing number of Western countries.
That is to say, it seems to be coming more and more, in vast sectors of the population, the conviction that before their actions are the same ideas of the hitherto booming social elites, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the general sense of the term, to have made their own time and to be more and more foreign to the opinions of the majorities.
The demand for leadership, in short, feeds underground a branching but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and the traditional political structures, which is manifested in the sudden "revolts" of the elections or in the sudden turns of the collective moods of these last and last times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of the consensualists.
One has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rituals, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats, would say, are finding it increasingly difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not now taking shape in the deep layers of Western societies and which the economic crisis is invigorating, growing, potentially agitating.
In the face of all this, to speak of a "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not at all.
The superglue for walking on walls
Defeat the laws of gravity thanks to a super glue and in the future walk on the walls like Spiderman.
It is the goal of several American research centers and now a team of four institutions has come very close to it.
With a sticker of only 2.5 square centimeters the scholars managed to glue a body of 100 kilograms on a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of some researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the team is an evolution of existing ones that use a particular carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
“The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti,” explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists were inspired by the gecko’s legs, covered with microscopic hairs that ensure perfect adhesion to the animal.
Tests conducted on different materials, such as glass, Teflon and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles and at the same time "detaches easily from the wall," explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's Faculty of Engineering.
“This material could be useful as a transient adhesive,” adds Dai Liming.
Maybe to walk on the walls just like Spiderman? Maybe yes, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use as the connection between electronic devices, because carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications may concern aerospace engineering.
No superheroes at the moment.
OTHER RESEARCH – The University of Berkeley, California, is also devoting itself to the search for a new adhesive.
In an article in the journal of the American Chemical Society, Californian scholars presented an adhesive made up of microfibers like hair that self-clean from dust while moving on a surface to always maintain perfect adhesion.
