Open Office, here is the third edition of the package "anti-Microsoft"
It is the day of the release of OpenOffice.org 3.0, the open source suite of personal productivity that aims to reach more and more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, as a free alternative to the more well-known Microsoft Office.
After almost a year of work by voluntary developers, behind whose back SUN Microsystem guards, the new Open Office is shown to the general public with several novelties: to the welcome screen and to the revised interface and made less spartan, more substantial ones are added such as the native compatibility for the operating system Apple Mac OS X and the support for the new format ODF (Open Document Format) standard 1.2.
Attention is also paid to interoperability with the Office 2007 suite, Open Office is able to open documents with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Some interesting features specific to some forms such as the one that allows you to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, useful for example to send them by email, or the ability to import PDF files in the graphic processing module, while retaining the original appearance of the page.
Also on this front you can create "hybrid PDF" documents, which match the typical graphics of the Adobe format with the elements of a spreadsheet or a text processor.
Collaboration is an element that has received several improvements within the applications: in the spreadsheet you can intervene with multiple hands between different users, avoiding conflicts on changes, in the word processor, each collaborator is assigned a color in the comments for better recognisability during revision.
Some companies are also working to bring some features of OpenOffice to the Web (on the cloud), and in the coming weeks they are expected to release the final result.
The Italian version can be downloaded at http://en.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html and was added to the English version that was on the mirrors since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, as usual the suite is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request the installation CD can also be shipped home or at the workplace.
And if the theme of gratuitousness can be a drag for the diffusion in homes, it is precisely in the business field that Open Office the suite tries the big bet, already being able to count on several projects carried out in the public administration and in schools.
And there are also companies that offer an ideal training, consulting and assistance service for small and medium-sized companies, which could open up business prospects.
Open Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for the corresponding videowriting of Word; Calc, is the spreadsheet that aims to replace Excel; Impress, for the emulate presentations of Powerpoint; Dbase, as in the case of the most famous Access is the program that allows you to work on databases; Draw, is finally the graphical module.
