Student victims of expensive-rents up to 900 euros for a room
The rent market for college students knows no crisis.
According to the latest survey by Sunia, the tenants’ union, taking a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now taken on very serious characteristics to the point that it excludes entire groups of young people from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families of origin should bear - explains the head of the study office of Sunia, Laura Mariani - in these cities the high demand from students has so distorted the market that it has triggered a process of generalized increase also for residents".
In the majority of cases, the rental offers then contain a series of violations: free, unregistered contracts, no limit on fees, sub-rents linked.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions are needed that, through the revision of taxation, can calm prices.
Looking at the details of the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room it goes from a minimum of 650 (Black Bands area) to an average value of 800 (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera area) to a maximum of 900 (Vittoria area).
In Florence a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room about 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a double bed, from 370 to 500 for a single.
In Rome in areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna) are asked about 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a bed in a double.
Values only slightly lower (550 euros for a single room) in areas close to the other universities (Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>).
You save only if you move to peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed and 450 a single in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar areas.
In Naples for a bed you need 300/450 euros, for a room you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with the highest prices in the areas Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari for a bed you need 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities prices are lower in absolute terms, but they have a greater weight in the city's economy.
Finally, in cities where the phenomenon of rents to non-EU students is more frequent, such as Perugia, there is an additional anomaly: the increase of about 25/30% in the fee applied to foreign students compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, the cities cancel the historical halls
Historical cinemas close in favor of Multiplexes.
“A city without movie theaters is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the large Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the outskirts of the great multisales and the consequent death by consumption of monosales in the central areas of the cities, is one of those events that seem inescapable and incontrovertible but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear are often historical places and full of memory, "it is as if a friend, an acquaintance with whom we have shared a piece of the street and many emotions, "says the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won Tornatore the Oscar and the Grand Prix of the Cannes jury, and that told the poetry of a provincial hall perhaps and the nostalgia for a way of life.
The figures provided by Anec, the main trade association, speak for themselves: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and the biggest expense is the cinemas in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures, Emilia-Romagna stands out with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to show that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian exercise has developed irrationally,” observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, “it is useful that new structures are built, but we should guarantee the survival of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its visitors are willing to move into multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the fund in favor of traders: the previous debt of the State is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector would need between 16 and 18 million euros a year".
The case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about the closures, decided to run for shelter with the signing of a protocol between the Municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to protect and promote single-room cinemas both in the historic center and on the outskirts.
Among the rules foreseen are tax facilitation measures for operators and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for parking and in some parking lots.
“It is an initiative that I like,” Giuseppe Tornatore observes, “and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna’s example by putting in place other measures.
It is certain, however, that to counter the overpowering of multiplexes traditional halls must also improve the quality of sound and image, because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New cinema Paradise", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or the Quirinale of Via Nazionale now closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the billboards blackened by the dust I turn to the other side.
