When the energy comes from the waves, the big ones now come into the field.
It is an exterminated field, occupying more than 70% of the planet’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources they have their eyes on, and now they are trying to get their hands on, giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years now and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now environmental demands and the new increase in oil give impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by offshore swell facilities.
This would be twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there would be the currents and the tides.
Colossi in the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in Northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years later to bet on marine energy are more and more and among these companies always devoted to traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies,” a spokesman for a company affiliated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, “and is considering cooperating with us.”
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the US Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a marine energy exploitation project in Alaska.
This is a not a small sign, especially considering that the US continues to extract oil in Alaska and recently President Bush has initiated a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, New York’s Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey’s Ocean Power are on the path of energy coming from the sea, and the sums invested so far, though not known in detail, indicate, according to observers, a rising interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts are talking about a technology still in its infancy, also because marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, plants such as the Portuguese one or some in Scotland are small in size and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, we must use technologies with a greater environmental impact.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The wave thrust, which causes the buoys to move up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure causes a turbine to run, which in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent ashore through submarine cables.
For now there are four such plants under design, pending only federal approval and some of the energy could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power is already producing power for a shopping mall and parking lot using six underwater turbines in New York’s East River.
The movement of water when there are tides rotates turbine blades, creating a rotating motion that powers a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say to the Institute for Electricity Research, deserves the potential of tides right now.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as an energy source.
It is precisely on tidal energy that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others overlooking the coast, have already invested $7.5 million in 2008 and planned investments of up to $35 million for 2009.
